  "prompt": "When and how did Gautama Buddha die?",
  "response": "Gautama Buddha, the founder of Buddhism, is traditionally believed to have died around 483 BCE, although some scholarly estimates suggest his lifespan may have extended into the 4th century BCE. His death is referred to as the **Parinirvana**, signifying his final passing beyond the cycle of birth and rebirth.\n\n### **Circumstances of His Death**\n\nAccording to Buddhist texts and traditions, Buddha's death occurred in the town of **Kushinagar**, which is in present-day Uttar Pradesh, India. The accounts describe that shortly before his passing, Buddha fell seriously ill after consuming a meal offered by a blacksmith named **Vakkhini**. The meal, often described as containing **sukara-maddava** (which can be translated as \"delicious pork\" or a special kind of truffle), is believed to have been the immediate cause of his illness. Some interpretations suggest that the meal contributed to complications leading to his **intestinal hemorrhage**, while others view it metaphorically, emphasizing the impermanent nature of all physical forms.\n\n### **Legacy**\n\nBuddha's **Parinirvana** marks the end of his earthly existence but also symbolizes the attainment of complete enlightenment and liberation from the cycle of samsara (rebirth). His teachings, preserved in various Buddhist scriptures, continue to influence millions of people worldwide.\n\n### **Historical Considerations**\n\nIt's important to note that historical records from the time of Gautama Buddha are limited, and much of what is known comes from Buddhist scriptures written centuries after his death. Consequently, while the traditional accounts provide a consistent narrative, exact historical details regarding his death may vary among different Buddhist traditions and scholarly interpretations.",
